abstract: The two funnymen stroll around Times Square in character as their aged and cantankerous alter egos in “Oh, Hello on Broadway.”
snippet: The two funnymen stroll around Times Square in character as their aged and cantankerous alter egos in “Oh, Hello on Broadway.”
lead_paragraph: A walk through Times Square typically requires a high tolerance for exasperation, and even more so when it is spent in the company of Gil Faizon and George St. Geegland.

abstract: Move slowly through the World Trade Center memorial plaza. Watch the names that flow by. Absorb the vast emptiness, the enormity of our loss, the passage of years.
snippet: Move slowly through the World Trade Center memorial plaza. Watch the names that flow by. Absorb the vast emptiness, the enormity of our loss, the passage of years.
lead_paragraph: Walk onto the plaza in Lower Manhattan and you hear the memorial before you see it — a whooshing through the oak trees. You soon realize it’s not the wind, but water. At the footprint of each tower, north and south, a vast square emptiness is bound by four walls of falling water, the pool below pouring into a smaller central void that flows out of sight. The memorial is black upon black, but the water casts reflections. Sunlight and mist make fragmentary rainbows that flicker as clouds go by.

abstract: Last week’s top galas included the Hampton Classic Grand Prix, and the 9/11 Memorial Dinner at Cipriani Wall Street.
snippet: Last week’s top galas included the Hampton Classic Grand Prix, and the 9/11 Memorial Dinner at Cipriani Wall Street.
lead_paragraph: Michael R. Bloomberg hosted his annual 9/11 Memorial Dinner, a benefit for the National September 11 Memorial and Museum, on Sept. 7 at Cipriani Wall Street. The event honored Ronald O. Perelman and Michael L. Corbat of Citigroup, and raised $3 million. The Hampton Classic Grand Prix on Sept. 4 capped off the summer social calendar, featuring world-class show jumping and celebrity spotting on a gorgeous Sunday afternoon.

abstract: As Michael Dell closes $67 billion merger, Meg Whitman sells off Hewlett Packard Enterprise’s software for $8.8 billion.
snippet: As Michael Dell closes $67 billion merger, Meg Whitman sells off Hewlett Packard Enterprise’s software for $8.8 billion.
lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Michael Dell and Meg Whitman may be business competitors, but they can each claim a technology industry superlative. One has overseen one of the largest mergers in the tech industry. The other has engineered its biggest breakup.

abstract: The flag, which was featured in a famous photograph of ground zero and disappeared soon after the attack, will again become a prominent part of Lower Manhattan.
snippet: The flag, which was featured in a famous photograph of ground zero and disappeared soon after the attack, will again become a prominent part of Lower Manhattan.
lead_paragraph: The moment was captured in a photograph, an unforgettable image that was seared in the world’s collective memory as a symbol of resilience: three firefighters raising an American flag amid the ruins of the World Trade Center on Sept. 11, 2001.

abstract: Mr. Espaillat, a Democrat who is favored to win a congressional seat in November, is trying to help two fellow Dominicans win state primaries.
snippet: Mr. Espaillat, a Democrat who is favored to win a congressional seat in November, is trying to help two fellow Dominicans win state primaries.
lead_paragraph: Adriano Espaillat’s victory in a Democratic primary for a New York congressional seat was a watershed for Dominican immigrants hoping to send one of their own to Washington for the first time.

snippet: The split illustrates a new dimension in the gun control debate, with party politics at times taking a rare back seat.
lead_paragraph: GLENOLDEN, Pa. — Senator Patrick J. Toomey hears a lot of things he would rather not these days, like the taunts of protesters outside a body shop here about his (actually nonexistent) relationship with Donald J. Trump.

headline_main: Gun Control Groups Divide Their Loyalties in Senate Races
headline_print_headline: Split Loyalty for Groups That Back Gun Control

abstract: The Legislature is broken and needs members who will put public interests ahead of their own.
snippet: The Legislature is broken and needs members who will put public interests ahead of their own.
lead_paragraph: The New York Legislature is still broken, even though its two leading bad actors — Sheldon Silver, the former Assembly speaker, and Dean Skelos, the former Senate majority leader — have been convicted of corruption and sentenced to prison. Besides prosecuting the criminals, changing Albany’s culture requires sending in people who will put public interests ahead of their own. Here are recommendations for some races in the Democratic primary on Sept. 13.

headline_main: Endorsements in New York Primary Races

abstract: Early in Mayor Bill de Blasio’s tenure, unions were among his biggest supporters. Now, with the possibility of a re-election fight looming, they are beginning to wonder if they should stick with him.
snippet: Early in Mayor Bill de Blasio’s tenure, unions were among his biggest supporters. Now, with the possibility of a re-election fight looming, they are beginning to wonder if they should stick with him.
lead_paragraph: As what would become one of the most controversial deals of Mayor Bill de Blasio’s administration — the removal of deed restrictions on a Lower East Side nursing home — hung in the balance, the health care workers union, 1199 S.E.I.U., sought to exert its influence through a series of emails and text messages to the mayor’s top officials.
